with%20a%20loss%20of%208%2C400.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20unemployment%20rate%20didn't%20see%20that%20much%20of%20a%20change%2C%20which%20was%20expected.%20The%20unemployment%20rate%20changed%20from%203.6%25%20in%20June%20to%203.5%25%20in%20July.%20The%20rate%20was%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.investing.com%2Feconomic-calendar%2Funemployment-rate-300%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eexpected%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20still%20be%203.6%25.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22raw%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2FWAvbf%2F7%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22US%20unemployment%20rate%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22450%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EAverage%20hourly%20earnings%20was%20up%204.4%25%20year%20over%20year%20in%20July.%20This%20percent%20change%20was%20also%204.4%25%20in%20January%2C%20April%2C%20and%20June%20this%20year.%20Looking%20just%20at%20the%20change%20over%20the%20month%2C%20hourly%20earnings%20increased%20by%200.4%25%2C%20which%20again%20was%20the%20case%20in%20April%20and%20June.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BToday's%20report%20shows%20that%20the%20job%20market%20is%20on%20a%20slow%20but%20steady%20path%20towards%20the%20soft%20landing%2C%26quot%3B%20Daniel%20Zhao%2C%20lead%20economist%20at%20Glassdoor%2C%20told%20Insider.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20overall%20labor%20force%20participation%20rate%20was%2062.6%25.%20That%20marks%20July%20the%20fifth%20straight%20month%20of%20this%20rate%2C%20as%20pointed%20out%20in%20Friday's%20news%20release%20from%20BLS.%20The%20prime-age%20labor%20force%20participation%20rate%20ticked%20down%20slightly%20from%2083.5%25%20in%20June%20to%2083.4%25%20in%20July.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20employment-population%20ratio%20was%20yet%20another%20data%20point%20that%20was%20little%20changed%20in%20July.%20That%20ratio%20was%2060.4%25%20in%20July%2C%20up%20from%2060.3%25%20in%20June.%20Both%20the%20%26quot%3Bnu